---
scope: src/service/docsRegistry
description: Build-time filesystem walker that discovers all markdown docs across four content roots and produces a deterministically-ordered 33-route registry with commit hashes and rendered HTML.
intent: >
  Walk four content roots (.aide/docs/, .claude/commands/, .claude/agents/,
  .claude/skills/) at build time, discover every .md file with zero exclusions,
  derive stable URL paths and slugs, inject per-file commit hashes from git,
  and return a deterministically-ordered DocRegistry that Next.js can hand
  directly to generateStaticParams. Every discovered file becomes a route — the
  registry is the single source of truth that makes drift between the shipped
  package contents and the rendered site structurally impossible.
outcomes:
  desired:
    - Every .md file under the four content roots becomes a DocRoute with a stable urlPath, an absPath, a git commit hash (or 'uncommitted' for untracked files), and a deterministic order value.
    - "The total route count is exactly 33: 9 methodology, 13 commands (aide.md + 12 subcommands under aide/), 9 agents, 2 skills."
    - Routes are ordered deterministically — section priority follows DOCS_CATEGORIES array order (methodology first, skills last), index.md sorts first within its section, then alphabetical by slug — so generateStaticParams output is stable across builds.
    - The orchestrator memoizes its output via a module-level cache so repeated calls within a single build return the same DocRegistry instance without re-walking the filesystem.
    - "getByKey accepts a DocRouteKey of the form `section/slug` and returns the matching route or undefined."
  undesired:
    - Any hardcoded list of doc filenames or slugs anywhere in the service — if a new .md file is added under a content root and the site is rebuilt, that file must appear as a new route automatically.
    - Silent failures — a file that exists on disk but is missing from the registry, or a commit hash that silently defaults to an empty string instead of 'uncommitted'.
    - Non-deterministic ordering — routes whose sort position changes between builds (e.g. sorted by mtime or inode order) break stable URL generation and make diffing the registry impossible.
    - A route whose urlPath does not match the pattern /docs/{methodology,commands,agents,skills}/<slug>.
---

## Context

The site's docs area renders directly from this repository's filesystem — the markdown files that ship with `@aidemd-mcp/server` are the docs. The registry is the build-time bridge between raw filesystem entries and Next.js static routes. It must discover files, not enumerate them, because the guarantee "add a file, get a route" is structural: it must be impossible to add a doc without it appearing on the site.

Four content roots exist today: `.aide/docs/` (9 methodology docs), `.claude/commands/` (13 commands — one top-level `aide.md` plus 12 subcommands under `aide/`), `.claude/agents/` (9 agents, all under `aide/`), `.claude/skills/` (2 skills — one `SKILL.md` per skill subfolder). Each root maps to one DocSection discriminant and one URL segment under `/docs/`.

The commit hash per file is the cite-as versioning mechanism the root intent spec calls non-negotiable. Every docs URL is permanently citable at `https://aidemd.dev/docs/<slug>?v=<commit>`, which means the registry must inject commit hashes at build time, not at request time.

## Strategy

**Walk the filesystem recursively with zero exclusion rules.** Use the Node 22 `readdir` recursive API and filter only by `isFile() && name.endsWith('.md')`. No allowlist, no denylist, no pattern matching beyond the extension filter. Adding a file automatically adds a route.

**Derive slugs from relative paths.** Strip the `.md` extension and replace OS path separators with `/`. The path relative to `absRoot` is the canonical slug. A file at `.aide/docs/aide-spec.md` has slug `aide-spec`; a file at `.claude/commands/aide/align.md` has slug `aide/align`. This rule is lossless and reversible.

**Special-case index.md for sort position only, not for URL derivation.** The slug for `index.md` is `index` (not empty string). It sorts first within its section so the section root page is always the first route.

**Inject commit hashes via `git log -1` per file.** Run synchronously at build time; wrap in a module-level Map cache keyed on absPath so each file is shelled out to git at most once per build. Return `'uncommitted'` on empty stdout — this is a named sentinel, not a silent default.

**Sort routes in three tiers: section priority, index-first, alphabetical slug.** Section priority is derived from the position of the category in DOCS_CATEGORIES (lower index = higher priority). Within a section, `index.md` (slug === 'index') sorts before all other slugs. Within the same section at the same index-or-not tier, sort alphabetically by slug. Assign the final `order` integer after sorting.

**Memoize at the orchestrator level.** A module-level `let cached` variable holds the DocRegistry after the first call. All subsequent calls return the cached value. This prevents redundant filesystem walks when Next.js calls `generateStaticParams` and page components in the same build process.

**Accept a Highlighter instance as input to renderMarkdown.** The markdown-to-HTML pipeline (remark to rehype to shiki) takes a prebuilt Highlighter so the highlighter singleton from step 5 can be shared across all 33 routes rather than constructed once per render.

## Good examples

A correctly discovered and ordered route for the methodology index:

```
{ section: 'methodology', slug: 'index', title: 'AIDE', urlPath: '/docs/methodology/index', absPath: '/abs/path/.aide/docs/index.md', order: 0 }
```

A correctly discovered route for a nested command:

```
{ section: 'commands', slug: 'aide/align', title: 'Align', urlPath: '/docs/commands/aide/align', absPath: '/abs/path/.claude/commands/aide/align.md', order: 14 }
```

A correctly resolved commit hash for a committed file:

```
commit: 'b75834c'
```

A correctly resolved commit hash for an untracked file:

```
commit: 'uncommitted'
```

## Bad examples

A route whose slug is derived from the filename only, ignoring the subfolder: `.claude/commands/aide/align.md` producing slug `align` instead of `aide/align`. This collapses the namespace and produces URL collisions when two different subfolders have files with the same name.

A registry that returns `commit: ''` when git returns empty stdout. This is a silent default — the cite-as URL would read `?v=` with no hash, which looks like a bug rather than a named state.

A route with `urlPath: '/docs/aide/align'` instead of `/docs/commands/aide/align`. This omits the section segment and breaks the URL structure that the nav relies on.

An ordering that changes between builds because the filesystem returned files in inode order rather than alphabetical order. Any non-deterministic ordering breaks the stable-params guarantee.

## References

- `.aide/intent.aide` -- root intent spec; establishes the "zero exclusions" filesystem walk requirement, the cite-as URL commit hash contract, and the four content roots
- `src/data/docsCategories.ts` -- section priority order used by orderRoutes; single source of truth for absRoot paths and urlSegment values
- `src/types/docs.ts` -- DocRoute, DocRegistry, DocRouteKey, DocSection types the registry must satisfy
